diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can affect multiple organ systems and manifest with pericardial effusion, neurological symptoms (including psychosis and delirium), kidney involvement (proteinuria), and hematological abnormalities (leukopenia).

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This rheumatologic condition shares features with other systemic autoimmune diseases, including SLE, and can present with similar symptoms such as pericardial effusion, neurologic symptoms, proteinuria, and leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Infective Endocarditis
diagnoses.rationale: While more commonly associated with heart valve issues, infective endocarditis can lead to pericardial effusion, proteinuria due to renal involvement, and can cause a variety of systemic symptoms including psychiatric manifestations and leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Viral Infection (e.g., HIV, Hepatitis B, Hepatitis C)
diagnoses.rationale: Certain viral infections can cause a wide array of systemic symptoms, including pericardial effusion (though rarer), kidney involvement (proteinuria), neurological symptoms (psychosis, delirium), and hematologic abnormalities (leukopenia).

diagnoses.name: Thrombotic Thrombocytopenic Purpura (TTP)
diagnoses.rationale: Although TTP primarily involves thrombocytopenia, it can also present with neurological symptoms (such as psychosis and delirium), renal dysfunction (proteinuria), and in rare cases, cardiac involvement including pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.rationale: Sarcoidosis is a multisystem inflammatory disease that can present with pericardial effusion, neurological manifestations (including psychosis and delirium), renal involvement (proteinuria), and hematological abnormalities (including leukopenia).

diagnoses.name: Endocarditis
diagnoses.rationale: Non-infective endocarditis, including from autoimmune causes, can manifest with pericardial effusion, renal involvement (proteinuria), and various systemic symptoms including psychiatric symptoms and hematological abnormalities.

diagnoses.name: Post-streptococcal Glomerulonephritis
diagnoses.rationale: Though primarily a cause of renal symptoms (proteinuria), in severe cases, it can be associated with systemic symptoms including neurological manifestations. Association with pericardial effusion and leukopenia would be less common but possible in a broader systemic response.

diagnoses.name: Schizophrenia
diagnoses.rationale: While schizophrenia is primarily a psychiatric diagnosis characterized by psychosis, in very rare instances, patients with severe untreated schizophrenia might present with physical symptoms secondary to their psychiatric condition, including poor self-care leading to systemic manifestations. Direct association with pericardial effusion, proteinuria, and leukopenia would be unusual and likely indicative of an additional underlying condition.

diagnoses.name: Drug-Induced Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.rationale: Certain medications can induce a lupus-like syndrome, presenting with symptoms similar to SLE, including pericardial effusion, neuropsychiatric symptoms, renal involvement (proteinuria), and hematological abnormalities (leukopenia).

diagnoses: Viral infections (such as HIV, Hepatitis C)

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can present with serositis (i.e., pericarditis), arthritis, fever, leukopenia, and neuropsychiatric manifestations (including delirium).

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.rationale: Though now rare in developed countries, rheumatic fever can cause fever, leukopenia, pericarditis, and could potentially lead to synovial involvement.

diagnoses.name: Adult-onset Still's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Characterized by spiking fever, arthritis or synovitis, and leukocytosis, but leukopenia can occur. It can also involve pericarditis and transient rash.

diagnoses.name: Viral Infection
diagnoses.rationale: Various viral infections can present with fever, leukopenia, and delirium. Specific viruses (e.g., Coxsackievirus) can also cause pericarditis.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Endocarditis
diagnoses.rationale: While more commonly associated with fever and heart involvement, can occasionally present with leukopenia, delirium due to septic emboli, and can cause reactive synovitis.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: RA can present with synovitis, fever, and in more severe cases, leukopenia and pericarditis due to systemic involvement.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD may present with features overlapping various connective tissue disorders, including pericarditis, synovitis, fever, leukopenia, and neuropsychiatric symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.rationale: While primarily affecting the lungs, sarcoidosis can involve the heart (pericarditis), joints (arthritis), cause fever, leukopenia, and neurosarcoidosis can lead to delirium.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.rationale: Extrapulmonary TB can cause widespread systemic symptoms including fever, leukopenia, pericarditis (in pericardial TB), and can affect joints.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.rationale: In its disseminated form, Lyme disease can cause arthritis/synovitis, myocarditis or pericarditis, and fever. Neurological involvement can sometimes present with confusion or delirium.

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.rationale: Hypoferritinemia is a hallmark of iron deficiency, which can lead to anemia causing dyspnea and chronic tiredness that can be perceived as back pain.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Can lead to iron deficiency due to malabsorption, and its dermatitis herpetiformis manifestation could be misinterpreted as alopecia.

diagnoses.name: Plummer-Vinson Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Characterized by iron deficiency anemia, dysphagia due to esophageal webs, and can indirectly cause dyspnea. Alopecia could be a secondary feature due to nutritional deficiencies.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.rationale: Can cause hair loss (alopecia) and may lead to dyspnea and fatigue. Hypothyroidism can sometimes contribute to iron deficiency as well.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: An autoimmune disorder that can cause chronic back pain and has been associated with anemia and alopecia. Lung involvement can cause dyspnea.

diagnoses.name: Lupus (Systemic Lupus Erythematosus)
diagnoses.rationale: A systemic autoimmune disease that can cause chronic back pain, dyspnea, alopecia, and hypoferritinemia.

diagnoses.name: Scleroderma
diagnoses.rationale: A connective tissue disease that can cause dysphagia due to esophageal involvement, dyspnea, and alopecia. It may also cause chronic back pain.

diagnoses.name: Polymyositis
diagnoses.rationale: An inflammatory disease causing muscle weakness which can lead to dysphagia and chronic back pain. Dyspnea may occur due to respiratory muscle weakness.

diagnoses.name: Psoriatic Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: Can cause chronic back pain and alopecia. Patients might experience fatigue, which can be perceived as dyspnea.

diagnoses.name: Inflammatory Bowel Disease (Crohn’s Disease and Ulcerative Colitis)
diagnoses.rationale: It can lead to iron deficiency due to blood loss and malabsorption, alopecia due to nutritional deficiencies, and chronic back pain associated with spondylarthritis. Dysphagia and dyspnea could be less common symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions where the immune system mistakenly attacks the body, which could explain the eosinophilia and potentially contribute to inflammation causing symptoms like folliculitis.

diagnoses.name: Allergic reactions
diagnoses.description: Allergies could lead to eosinophilia and inflammatory skin conditions like folliculitis, along with possibly aggravating hyperactivity through discomfort or sleep disruption.

diagnoses.name: Neurological disorders
diagnoses.description: Certain neurological conditions could underlie the occurrence of blepharospasm and contribute indirectly to autonomic dysregulation seen in conditions like postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome (POTS).

diagnoses.name: Infectious diseases
diagnoses.description: Some infections can lead to a wide array of symptoms, including skin manifestations (e.g., folliculitis), hyperactivity (due to systemic effects or fever), and eosinophilia (as part of the immune response).

diagnoses.name: Endocrine disorders
diagnoses.description: Disorders affecting hormone levels can cause symptoms like hyperactivity and might indirectly contribute to folliculitis through changes in skin condition or even influence autonomic functions related to POTS.

diagnoses.name: Primary Immunodeficiency Disorders
diagnoses.description: These disorders can lead to both increased susceptibility to infections, potentially causing folliculitis and eosinophilia, and dysregulation of normal immune responses, possibly contributing to the development of POTS.

diagnoses.name: Psychiatric disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions such as anxiety could theoretically contribute to or exacerbate symptoms like hyperactivity, and POTS has been linked with increased rates of anxiety disorders.

diagnoses.name: Dermatological conditions
diagnoses.description: Specific skin conditions might directly cause folliculitis and have indirect relationships with systemic symptoms like eosinophilia.

diagnoses.name: Hypersensitivity syndromes
diagnoses.description: Complex conditions characterized by an exaggerated immune response to different stimuli, potentially explaining the eosinophilia and dermatological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Metabolic disorders
diagnoses.description: These could underlie several of the symptoms due to the disruption of normal metabolic processes, potentially influencing everything from energy levels (hyperactivity) to skin health (folliculitis).

diagnoses: Oral Leukoplakia related to HPV Infection

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that causes the bone marrow to make too many red blood cells. These excess cells thicken the blood, slowing its flow, and can cause complications such as fatigue and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormones. Symptoms can include fatigue, weakness, and difficulty concentrating or finding words.

diagnoses.name: Myasthenia Gravis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that causes weakness in the skeletal muscles, which are responsible for breathing and moving parts of the body. Symptoms can include fatigue and episodic weakness.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.description: Anxiety can manifest physically and mentally, causing symptoms like palpitations, fatigue, and sometimes difficulty with concentration and word-finding.

diagnoses.name: Hyperthyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition where the thyroid gland is overactive and produces too much thyroid hormone, leading to symptoms including palpitations, fatigue, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: This occurs when the body lacks enough iron to produce healthy red blood cells, leading to symptoms such as fatigue, weakness, and potentially complications leading to polycythemia.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)
diagnoses.description: A group of lung diseases that block airflow and make it difficult to breathe, leading to symptoms like fatigue and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Sleep Apnea
diagnoses.description: A disorder in which breathing repeatedly stops and starts during sleep, causing restless sleep and leading to symptoms such as fatigue and episodic weakness during the day.

diagnoses.name: Cardiac Arrhythmias
diagnoses.description: Conditions of irregular heartbeat, which can cause palpitations, fatigue, and episodic weakness due to decreased cardiac output.

diagnoses.name: Dehydration
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by not drinking enough fluids, leading to symptoms like fatigue, weakness, and in severe cases, complications that could resemble polycythemia due to concentrated blood volume.

diagnoses: Inflammatory bowel disease (Crohn's disease and Ulcerative colitis)

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition where the kidneys don't work as well as they should, leading to abnormal electrolytes and an increased risk of infections.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic disorder causing repeated episodes of swelling (angioedema).

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormones, can cause abnormal electrolytes and increased susceptibility to infection.

diagnoses.name: Liver Cirrhosis
diagnoses.description: Long-term liver damage can lead to abnormal electrolyte balances and increased susceptibility to infections due to compromised immunity.

diagnoses.name: Addison's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder that occurs when your body produces insufficient amounts of certain hormones produced by your adrenal glands, leading to abnormal electrolytes and mood swings including anxiety.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can cause a wide range of symptoms, including abnormal electrolytes, increased susceptibility to infection, and anxiety.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Myeloid Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that affects the blood and bone marrow, leading to basophilia and an increased susceptibility to infections.

diagnoses.name: Myelodysplastic Syndromes
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders caused by poorly formed or dysfunctional blood cells, leading to increased susceptibility to infections and abnormalities in electrolytes.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) severely impairs the immune system, leading to increased susceptibility to infections, electrolyte imbalances, and psychological symptoms such as anxiety.

diagnoses.name: Primary Immunodeficiency
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders where the primary defect is in the cells of the immune system, leading to increased susceptibility to infections and possibly electrolyte disturbances due to associated conditions.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: A disease involving abnormal collections of inflammatory cells that form lumps known as granulomas. The condition can affect the lungs, lymph nodes, eyes, and skin.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that occurs when your body's immune system attacks your own tissues and organs. Inflammation caused by lupus can affect many different body systems.

diagnoses.name: Fabry Disease
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that results from the buildup of a particular type of fat, called globotriaosylceramide, in the body's cells. It can lead to pain, kidney problems, heart attack, and stroke.

diagnoses.name: IgG4-related Disease
diagnoses.description: An immune-mediated condition that can cause inflammation in your body's organs and tissues, leading to fibrosis and swelling.

diagnoses.name: Amyloidosis
diagnoses.description: A rare disease that occurs when a substance called amyloid builds up in your organs. Amyloidosis can affect the heart, kidneys, liver, spleen, nervous system, and digestive tract.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) damages the immune system and weakens your ability to fight everyday infections and disease. Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS) is the name used to describe a number of potentially life-threatening infections and illnesses that happen when your immune system has been severely damaged by the HIV virus.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic disorder that causes severe swelling, particularly of the face and airways, and abdominal cramping.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: Cancer that begins in infection-fighting cells of the immune system, called lymphocytes. These cells are in the lymph nodes, spleen, thymus, bone marrow, and other parts of the body.

diagnoses.name: Graft-versus-host disease (GVHD)
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs when donor bone marrow or stem cells attack the recipient. GVHD can manifest in various forms, affecting the skin, eyes, lungs, liver, and digestive tract.

diagnoses.name: Wegener's Granulomatosis (Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis)
diagnoses.description: An uncommon disorder that causes inflammation of the blood vessels in your nose, sinuses, throat, lungs, and kidneys.

diagnoses: Drug Reaction with Eosinophilia and Systemic Symptoms (DRESS)

diagnoses.name: Viral Infection
diagnoses.reasoning: Monocytosis can often be a response to viral infections, which can also explain lymphadenitis (swollen lymph nodes) and laryngitis.

diagnoses.name: Bacterial Infection
diagnoses.reasoning: Similar to viral infections, bacterial pathogens can cause monocytosis, laryngitis, and lymphadenitis. Difficulty focusing vision and hyperactivity may be less directly related but could be symptomatic of systemic infection or its effects on the body.

diagnoses.name: Mononucleosis
diagnoses.reasoning: Caused by the Epstein-Barr virus, it can lead to monocytosis, swollen lymph nodes (lymphadenitis), and throat inflammation (laryngitis). Hyperactivity and visual problems are less common but can occur, especially in the context of fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL)
diagnoses.reasoning: While less common, ALL can present with lymphadenitis due to lymphoid hyperplasia, monocytosis, and various neurological symptoms that might explain difficulty focusing vision and hyperactivity due to central nervous system involvement.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.reasoning: This inflammatory disease often affects the lungs, skin, and lymph nodes leading to lymphadenitis. Neurosarcoidosis can affect the brain, potentially leading to vision issues and hyperactivity. Monocytosis might occur as part of the systemic inflammatory response.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.reasoning: SLE is an autoimmune disease that can lead to widespread inflammation, affecting various organs and systems. This includes potential lymph node enlargement (lymphadenitis), neurological and ocular manifestations such as difficulty focusing vision, and monocytosis due to chronic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA)
diagnoses.reasoning: While primarily affecting joints, RA can also lead to systemic symptoms including lymphadenopathy (lymphadenitis) and, in rare cases, eye involvement and neurological symptoms (which might manifest as hyperactivity and difficulty focusing vision). Monocytosis can be seen in chronic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.reasoning: TB can cause lymphadenitis, especially in the neck (scrofula). While less common in developed countries, it can also lead to systemic symptoms including monocytosis. TB affecting the central nervous system could potentially explain neurological symptoms, though these are generally more severe.

diagnoses.name: Toxoplasmosis
diagnoses.reasoning: This parasitic infection can affect the lymph nodes, cause monocytosis, and may involve the nervous system, potentially explaining the combination of symptoms including vision difficulties.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.reasoning: Early stages of HIV or advanced stages of AIDS can present with monocytosis, lymphadenitis as a result of opportunistic infections, neurological complications that may affect vision and behavior, and possibly laryngitis due to opportunistic infections.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormones. Can cause delayed puberty, alopecia (hair loss), and dyslipidemia.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.description: A hormonal disorder common among women of reproductive age. PCOS can cause dyslipidemia, delayed puberty, and alopecia.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A group of diseases that affect how your body uses blood sugar (glucose). Diabetes can lead to dyslipidemia and is associated with conditions like alopecia.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition where the kidneys do not work effectively. It can cause dyslipidemia and is associated with conditions like interstitial cystitis.

diagnoses.name: Cushing's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by prolonged exposure to high levels of cortisol. Can cause dyslipidemia, alopecia, and delays in puberty.

diagnoses.name: Eating Disorders
diagnoses.description: Includes anorexia nervosa, bulimia nervosa, and binge-eating disorder. Eating disorders can cause delayed puberty, dyslipidemia, and alopecia.

diagnoses.name: Turner Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A chromosomal disorder affecting females, where one of the X chromosomes is missing or partially missing. It can cause delayed puberty and dyslipidemia.

diagnoses.name: Thyroiditis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the thyroid gland, leading to hypothyroidism or hyperthyroidism. Can cause dyslipidemia and alopecia.

diagnoses.name: Alopecia Areata
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that causes hair to come out in clumps or patches. While primarily affecting hair, it can be associated with other autoimmune conditions that could indirectly relate to the other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Growth Hormone Deficiency
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by the inadequate secretion of growth hormone from the pituitary gland, leading to delayed growth and puberty.

diagnoses.name: Kounis Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A type of allergic reaction to certain drugs, conditions, or stings that leads to acute coronary syndrome. It can manifest with chest pain, difficulty breathing, and sometimes wheezing.

diagnoses.name: Asthma
diagnoses.description: A chronic condition that affects the airways in the lungs, leading to difficulty breathing, wheezing, and shortness of breath.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.description: A digestive disorder where stomach acid or bile irritates the food pipe lining, causing dyspepsia and potentially leading to symptoms like difficulty concentrating due to discomfort or pain.

diagnoses.name: Irritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS)
diagnoses.description: A common disorder affecting the large intestine, causing symptoms like cramping, abdominal pain, bloating, gas, and dyspepsia. It may also affect bowel habits, but doesn't usually cause external hemorrhoids.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.description: A mental health disorder characterized by feelings of worry, anxiety, or fear that are strong enough to interfere with one’s daily activities. Symptoms may include difficulty concentrating.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Reactions
diagnoses.description: The body's immune system reacts to a foreign substance, such as pollen, bee venom, pet dander, or food, causing symptoms such as wheezing, itching, or swelling.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory lung disease that causes obstructed airflow from the lungs, symptoms include breathing difficulty, cough, mucus (sputum) production, and wheezing.

diagnoses.name: Hyperthyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland is overactive and produces too much thyroid hormone, leading to symptoms such as difficulty concentrating, weight loss, and potentially dyspepsia.

diagnoses.name: Peptic Ulcer Disease
diagnoses.description: Ulcers that form on the inner lining of the stomach or small intestine, causing pain and dyspepsia.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Venous Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the venous wall and/or valves in the leg veins are not working effectively, making it difficult for blood to return to the heart from the legs. This condition can lead to varicose veins and hemorrhoids.

diagnoses.reasoning: While not directly causing increased appetite, Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome can be associated with gastrointestinal symptoms including bloating and abdominal pain. It can also lead to easily bruised skin, which might be confused with striae.

diagnoses.name: Irritable Bowel Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: IBS can cause migratory abdominal pain and bloating. While it doesn't directly cause striae, increased appetite, or increased susceptibility to infection, its symptoms may overlap with conditions that do.

diagnoses.name: Crohn's Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Crohn’s disease can lead to abdominal pain and bloating. It can also increase susceptibility to infection due to the immune system being compromised, either by the disease itself or the medications used for treatment.

diagnoses.name: Ulcerative Colitis
diagnoses.reasoning: Similar to Crohn’s disease, Ulcerative Colitis can cause abdominal pain and increase susceptibility to infections. It's another form of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD).

diagnoses.name: Marfan Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: Although primarily affecting connective tissue, Marfan syndrome can sometimes be associated with gastrointestinal symptoms. It doesn't directly relate to the full set of symptoms described but could indirectly affect body systems in a way that mimics these symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Addison’s Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: This condition can increase appetite in the early stages and affect the skin, potentially leading to changes misunderstood as striae. It can also weaken the immune system, leading to an increased susceptibility to infection.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.reasoning: PCOS can cause weight gain, which might be mistaken for increased appetite, and can also lead to striae. It does not directly cause migratory abdominal pain or increased susceptibility to infections but can be associated with symptoms that resemble the described presentation.

diagnoses.name: Gastrointestinal Stromal Tumors (GIST)
diagnoses.reasoning: These tumors can cause abdominal pain and bloating. While they do not directly cause increased appetite, striae, or increased susceptibility to infections, their growth could indirectly affect bodily processes that lead to such symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Intestinal Parasites
diagnoses.reasoning: Infections like giardiasis can lead to bloating, abdominal pain, and increased appetite due to malabsorption. They directly increase susceptibility to further infections due to weakened intestinal health.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Inflammatory Conditions
diagnoses.rationale: This group includes autoimmune diseases which can cause skin manifestations (dyshydrotic eczema), inflammation of lymph nodes (lymphadenitis), oral lesions (leukoplakia), and might contribute to weight loss due to chronic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.rationale: HIV/AIDS can present with skin conditions such as dyshydrotic eczema, significant weight loss, lymphadenitis as a marker of immune system involvement, oral manifestations like leukoplakia, and might be associated with lower iron levels or anemia.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.rationale: While primarily indicated by hypoferritinemia, chronic iron deficiency anemia can contribute to systemic symptoms such as weight loss and possibly exacerbate conditions like dyshydrotic eczema due to overall poor skin health.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.rationale: Includes both Hodgkin and Non-Hodgkin lymphoma, which can cause lymphadenitis, weight loss, and can be associated with skin conditions and oral leukoplakia due to immune system dysfunction.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.rationale: Sarcoidosis is characterized by the growth of tiny inflammatory cells in different parts of the body, including skin (possibly leading to symptoms resembling dyshydrotic eczema), lymph nodes, and can also cause weight loss and systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.rationale: TB can cause lymphadenitis, weight loss, and sometimes skin issues. While dyshydrotic eczema specifically isn't a direct symptom of TB, skin manifestations can occur. Hypoferritinemia could reflect anemia of chronic disease.

diagnoses.name: Syphilis
diagnoses.rationale: Secondary syphilis can present with skin rashes and lesions that might be confused with dyshydrotic eczema, causes lymphadenitis, can lead to oral manifestations like leukoplakia, and might contribute to systemic symptoms like weight loss.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.rationale: Though not directly causing these conditions, poorly controlled diabetes can lead to skin infections that mimic dyshydrotic eczema, increase the risk for infections that might present as lymphadenitis, and affect overall nutritional status, contributing to weight loss.

diagnoses.name: Graft-versus-host disease (GVHD)
diagnoses.rationale: In post-transplant patients, GVHD can cause skin conditions (including eczema-like rashes), lymphadenopathy, and oral involvement such as leukoplakia, along with systemic symptoms like weight loss.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Polyglandular Syndromes
diagnoses.rationale: These syndromes are characterized by the occurrence of multiple endocrine gland deficiencies. They can indirectly contribute to or exacerbate conditions such as dyshydrotic eczema, lymphadenitis, and may feature weight loss and oral manifestations due to the overarching autoimmune activity and potential nutritional deficiencies.

Squamous Cell Carcinoma of the Head and Neck

diagnoses.name: Hypereosinophilic Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by a persistently elevated eosinophil count in the blood for at least six months without an apparent cause, which could manifest alongside symptoms like fatigue, cough, and congestion.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Rhinitis
diagnoses.description: An allergic response causing itchy, watery eyes, sneezing, and other similar symptoms. The condition can contribute to obstructive sleep apnea due to nasal congestion.

diagnoses.name: Asthma
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your airways narrow and swell and may produce extra mucus. This can make breathing difficult and trigger coughing, wheezing, and shortness of breath. Anxiety and stress can worsen asthma symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Sinusitis
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by the inflammation of the sinuses lasting for more than 12 weeks. Symptoms include congestion, facial pain or pressure, and might contribute to sleep disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Common Variable Immune Deficiency (CVID)
diagnoses.description: An immunodeficiency disorder characterized by a low level of antibodies, which can lead to an increased susceptibility to infections, including sinus and lung infections, potentially leading to symptoms like congestion.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition where stomach contents come back up into the esophagus causing symptoms like heartburn. GERD can aggravate or mimic symptoms of asthma and obstructive sleep apnea.

diagnoses.name: Obstructive Sleep Apnea Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by repeated breathing interruptions during sleep due to the obstruction of the upper airway. Symptoms can include daytime sleepiness and fatigue, potentially affecting psychological well-being and contributing to anxiety.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.description: A group of mental disorders characterized by significant feelings of anxiety and fear. Anxiety can exacerbate symptoms of other conditions or arise as a response to dealing with chronic illnesses.

diagnoses.name: Eosinophilic Gastroenteritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory condition affecting the stomach and small intestine characterized by eosinophilic infiltration. Symptoms may include nausea, diarrhea, abdominal pain, and it can affect nutrient absorption, leading to general health decline.

diagnoses.name: Atopic Dermatitis
diagnoses.description: A condition making your skin red and itchy. It's common in children but can occur at any age. Atopic dermatitis is long-lasting (chronic) and tends to flare periodically. It may be accompanied by asthma or hay fever.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and pain in any part of your body. It's characterized by flares and remissions and can affect the joints, skin, brain, lungs, kidneys, and blood vessels, causing widespread symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Scleroderma
diagnoses.description: A group of autoimmune diseases that may result in changes to the skin, blood vessels, muscles, and internal organs. Symptoms can include skin thickening, stiffness, and pain; also, it may cause visible blood vessels, skin ulcers, and fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet. Besides joint problems, RA can also affect skin, eyes, lungs, heart, and blood vessels.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and a distinctive skin rash. The condition can affect adults and children.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Hemorrhagic Telangiectasia (HHT)
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that leads to abnormal blood vessel formation. Symptoms include nosebleeds, skin telangiectasias, anemia, and blood in the stool.

diagnoses.name: Cutaneous Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A form of lupus that is limited to the skin. It presents as a rash that can be exacerbated by sun exposure. It may appear as red patches or skin ulcers.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare autoimmune disease with overlapping features of three other connective tissue diseases: lupus, scleroderma, and polymyositis. It may manifest with rashes, joint pain, muscle weakness, and fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Polymyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that causes muscle weakness affecting both sides of the body. Additional signs and symptoms include fatigue, muscle pain, and difficulty swallowing.

diagnoses.name: Behcet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout your body. The disease can lead to numerous signs and symptoms that may seem unrelated at first glance, including mouth sores, genital sores, eye inflammation, and skin rashes including ulcers.

diagnoses.name: Porphyria
diagnoses.description: A group of liver disorders in which substances called porphyrins build up, negatively affecting the skin or nervous system. Symptoms might include skin sensitivity to the sunlight, blisters, itching, and swelling.

diagnoses: Diabetes Mellitus Type 1 or Type 2 with complications

diagnoses.name: Systemic Mastocytosis
diagnoses.description: A disorder where mast cells accumulate in the skin and/or internal organs which could explain the combination of dermatographism, angioedema, and gastrointestinal symptoms like diarrhea. Hypertension can occur as a secondary symptom due to the release of mediators from mast cells.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder marked by recurrent episodes of severe swelling (angioedema). The most common areas of the body to develop swelling are the limbs, face, intestinal tract, and airway. Diarrhea can occur when the intestinal tract is involved. Dermatographism can sometimes be noted.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, potentially life-threatening allergic reaction that can result in angioedema, dermatographism, and hypertension due to the sudden release of chemical substances from mast cells and basophils. It doesn't typically cause hypoferritinemia or chronic diarrhea, but acute symptoms could align.

diagnoses.name: Carcinoid Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A group of symptoms associated with carcinoid tumors. These tumors secrete chemicals into the bloodstream, leading to flushing, diarrhea, and, in rare cases, skin manifestations that could be misinterpreted as dermatographism. Hypertension can also occur.

diagnoses.name: Gastrointestinal Disorders
diagnoses.description: Certain GI disorders, especially those involving malabsorption such as celiac disease, can lead to diarrhea and hypoferritinemia due to poor iron absorption. Secondary skin manifestations may occur, including dermatographism, in response to allergens or irritants.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Urticaria
diagnoses.description: A condition where the skin develops hives and itchy red patches for more than six weeks for no apparent reason. Dermatographism is a common symptom in chronic urticaria, and angioedema may occur as well.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions like systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) can indirectly cause a wide variety of symptoms including dermatographism and angioedema due to immune complex deposition, diarrhea from gastrointestinal involvement, hypoferritinemia from chronic disease, and hypertension due to kidney involvement.

diagnoses.name: Hypereosinophilic Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by high numbers of eosinophils in the blood and tissues, which can cause damage and inflammation, leading to skin manifestations similar to dermatographism, GI disturbances like diarrhea, and possibly angioedema.

diagnoses.name: Mast Cell Activation Syndrome (MCAS)
diagnoses.description: A condition where mast cells inappropriately release chemical mediators, leading to symptoms such as dermatographism, angioedema, diarrhea, and in some cases, hypoferritinemia due to chronic gastrointestinal loss of iron.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where the ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, causing diarrhea and hypoferritinemia due to malabsorption. Dermatographism and angioedema are not hallmark symptoms but can coexist in patients with multiple immune-related conditions.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, life-threatening allergic reaction that can occur suddenly after exposure to an allergen. Symptoms include hypotension, abdominal cramps, angioedema, and potentially syncope.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic disorder characterized by sudden episodes of swelling (angioedema) in various parts of the body, including the abdomen, face, limbs, and airway. Abdominal cramps and hypotension may occur during episodes.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Shock Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, life-threatening complication of certain types of bacterial infections. Symptoms include hypotension, abdominal cramps, and a rash that can resemble a sunburn.

diagnoses.name: Addison's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder that occurs when the adrenal glands do not produce enough of their hormones. Symptoms include hypotension, abdominal cramps, and in severe cases might lead to syncope.

diagnoses.name: Mastocytosis
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by the accumulation of mast cells in the skin and other parts of the body. Symptoms can include abdominal cramps, angioedema, hypotension, syncope, and pruritus.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Capillary Leak Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder characterized by the massive leakage of plasma from the bloodstream into body cavities and muscles, leading to hypotension, and possibly abdominal cramps and syncope.

diagnoses.name: Hypovolemic Shock
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from acute blood loss or dehydration causing hypotension, which may be associated with abdominal cramps if internal bleeding or severe dehydration is present.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylactoid Reactions
diagnoses.description: Similar to anaphylaxis, these reactions do not require prior sensitization to an allergen. Symptoms can include hypotension, abdominal cramps, angioedema, and syncope.

diagnoses.name: Food Allergy
diagnoses.description: An immune system reaction that occurs soon after eating certain foods, symptoms can include abdominal cramps, angioedema, hypotension, and in severe cases, anaphylaxis.

diagnoses.name: Carcinoid Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Occurs when a carcinoid tumor secretes certain chemicals into your bloodstream, causing symptoms like abdominal cramps, pruritus, and flushing. In rare cases, it may cause hypotension.

diagnoses.name: Stroke

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy

diagnoses.name: Neuromyelitis Optica
diagnoses.description: A heterogeneous condition that affects the optic nerves and spinal cord, resulting in various neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: Can cause various neurological issues due to its role in myelin formation and neurological function.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by Borrelia bacteria, spread by ticks. Neurological manifestations can include paresthesia and ataxia.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.details: Migraine headaches can cause severe head pain, nausea, weakness, and numbness or tingling.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.details: Multiple sclerosis (MS) can lead to numbness, weakness, balance problems, and headaches.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.details: A stroke can cause sudden numbness, weakness on one side of the body, and severe headache.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.details: A TIA or 'mini stroke' can manifest with temporary numbness, weakness, and headache, but symptoms usually resolve within 24 hours.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Neuropathy
diagnoses.details: Neuropathy from diabetes can cause tingling, pain, numbness, and weakness in various parts of the body.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumors
diagnoses.details: Brain tumors can lead to headaches, numbness, weakness, and changes in cognitive or physical abilities.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.details: Severe anemia can cause weakness, headaches, and sometimes numbness in extremities due to poor oxygen supply.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.details: Lyme disease can cause headaches, weakness, and numbness or tingling in the limbs.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.details: A deficiency in Vitamin B12 can cause weakness, headaches, and numbness or tingling in hands and feet.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.details: Meningitis, an inflammation of the brain and spinal cord membranes, can cause severe headache, weakness, and numbness.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. Symptoms may include sudden weakness, difficulty speaking, and vision problems.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Migraine with aura is a type of migraine that involves visual disturbances (scintillation) and other neurological symptoms before the actual headache begins. These symptoms can include muscle weakness, difficulty speaking (aphasia), and nausea or vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. A TIA usually lasts only a few minutes and doesn't cause permanent damage. Symptoms can include sudden weakness, aphasia, and visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A brain tumor involves a mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Depending on the tumor's location, it can cause weakness, problems with vision (scintillation), vomiting, and difficulty with speech (aphasia).

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis is a disease of the central nervous system that can cause a wide range of symptoms, including vision problems, weakness, and difficulty speaking. Some people with MS may also experience nausea or vomiting during flare-ups.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: Epilepsy is a central nervous system disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness. Severe episodes can manifest with a range of symptoms including aphasia, visual disturbances, and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: Meningitis is an inflammation of the membranes (meninges) surrounding your brain and spinal cord. The swelling from meningitis typically triggers symptoms such as headache, fever, and a stiff neck. Advanced cases can lead to neurological symptoms such as weakness, visual problems, vomiting, and difficulty speaking.

diagnoses.name: Metabolic Encephalopathy
diagnoses.description: Metabolic encephalopathy involves a range of neurological impairments due to the dysfunction of metabolic processes. Symptoms can vary widely but often include confusion, visual disturbances, weakness, vomiting, and difficulty with speech.

diagnoses.name: Subarachnoid Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: A subarachnoid hemorrhage is bleeding in the space between the brain and the surrounding membrane. It is a critical condition that can cause intense headaches, vomiting, vision problems, weakness, and sometimes speech difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Encephalitis is inflammation of the brain, caused by infection or an autoimmune response. Symptoms can vary but often include fever, headache, weakness, seizures, visual disturbances, and problems with speech.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. Symptoms can include sudden numbness, confusion, trouble speaking, seeing or walking, and severe headache.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Migraines with aura (also known as classic migraines) are characterized by temporary visual disturbances (scintillations) and other neurological symptoms that appear about 10 to 60 minutes before the headache starts. Symptoms might include visual disturbances, sensory changes (parasthesia), and speech or language abnormalities (aphasia).

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a ministroke, a transient ischemic attack (TIA) is a brief, temporary disruption of blood supply to part of the brain, spinal cord, or retina, causing stroke-like symptoms but without lasting damage. Symptoms are similar to those of a stroke but last only a few minutes and usually less than 24 hours before disappearing completely.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A brain tumor consists of abnormal cells in the brain. It can be benign (noncancerous) or malignant (cancerous). Symptoms often include headaches, seizures, nausea, weakness, aphasia, and sensory disturbances such as paresthesia, depending on the tumor’s location.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a chronic illness involving your central nervous system (CNS). The immune system attacks myelin, the protective layer surrounding nerve fibers, causing inflammation and scar tissue. This can lead to a wide range of symptoms including fatigue, walking difficulties, numbness or weakness in one or more limbs, and partial or complete loss of vision in one eye at a time (often with pain during eye movement).

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: Epilepsy is a central nervous system (neurological) disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness. Specific types of epilepsy can produce sensory disturbances that mimic parasthesia, as well as other symptoms like nausea before a seizure (ictal nausea).

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: Meningitis is an inflammation of the membranes (meninges) surrounding your brain and spinal cord. The swelling from meningitis typically triggers symptoms such as headache, fever, and a stiff neck. Depending on the severity, it could also lead to confusion, seizures, and impaired neurological function, including aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: Vertebrobasilar insufficiency occurs when the blood flow through the vertebral and basilar arteries is compromised, which can lead to ischemia in the posterior part of the brain. Symptoms may include dizziness, vision problems, weakness, difficulty speaking (aphasia), nausea, and numbness or tingling (parasthesia).

diagnoses.name: Toxic Encephalopathy
diagnoses.description: Toxic encephalopathy refers to brain dysfunction caused by toxic substances, such as heavy metals, drugs, or other poisons, leading to various neurological symptoms including weakness, confusion, memory loss, and sensory symptoms such as parasthesia.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A brain abscess is a collection of pus, immune cells, and other material in the brain, usually from a bacterial or fungal infection. Symptoms may include headache, fever, nausea, vomiting, neurological deficits such as aphasia, and sensory abnormalities.
